{
  "text": "Although some previous studies have shown the association between prolonged QTc interval and cardiovascular mortality or all-cause mortality in the general population [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] , other studies suggest that the association is not consistent and the risk is likely to be small [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . There are several possible explanations for the positive association. Prolongation of QTc interval reflects prolonged ventricular repolarization and predisposes to sudden death. Prolonged QTc interval is associated with elevated sympathetic tone which may lead to elevated blood pressure, atherosclerosis, and cardiovascular events [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . It is less clear why prolonged QTc interval also predicts all-cause mortality. One possible explanation is that prolonged QTc is a marker of other disorders such as DM or neurohormone imbalance which may predispose to increased mortality. In our study, patients with QTc-ER > 445 ms are more likely to be older, female in gender, have DM, higher peak CK, higher NT-proBNP, and higher TIMI risk score for STEMI. However, Cox multivariable regression analysis shows that QTc-ER is still an independent predictor after adjusting the above baseline differences.",
